<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12038f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12038f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12038f"> 38(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> born 29/ix</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Je me suis &eacute;pris sit&ocirc;t, en v&eacute;rit&eacute;, de cette fameuse abbaye! Mes yeux de cinq ans l&apos;aper&ccedil;urent, dans le lointain brumeux de sa grande baie, &agrave; travers les arbres du Jardin des Plantes d&apos;Avranches, o&ugrave; les coll&eacute;giens prenaient leurs &eacute;bats; Tiphaine Raguenel, l&apos;astrologue du Mont Saint-Michel, m&apos;e&ucirc;t peut-&ecirc;tre pr&eacute;dit, si j&apos;avais sollicit&eacute; un horoscope de sa science divinatoire, que le nom de l&apos;archange viendrait souvent sous ma plume, puisque <mark>je suis n&eacute; un 29 septembre</mark>, jour de la f&ecirc;te du Prince des Milices C&eacute;lestes; mais je ne suis ni pr&eacute;somptueux ni superstitieux &agrave; ce point et je m&apos;explique tout naturellement pourquoi m&apos;ont tant s&eacute;duit les travaux historiques sur le Mont Saint-Michel. <br>[I was immediately taken, to be sure, by this famous abbey. As a five year old saw it, through the distant fog of the great bay, through the trees of the Garden of Plants in Avranches, where the college boys would frolic; Tiphaine Raguenel, the astrologer of the Mont-Saint-Michel, could have told me, if I had asked for horoscope of her divination arts, that the name of the archangel would often come out of my pen, because I was born on 29 September, the feast-day of the Prince of the Heavenly Host; but I am neither so presumptuous nor so superstitious, so I had better explain why I so much like the historical works on the Mont-Saint-Michel. <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 2-3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
